1 otherwise, the following definitions apply:
2 (1) "Kratom" means the plant Mitragyna speciosa or any part of that plant.
3 (2) "Kratom extract" means a substance or compound obtained by extraction of the Mitragyna
4 speciosa leaf that is intended for ingestion and contains more than trace amounts of Mitragyna speciosa and
5 contains other alkaloids of the kratom plant, and which does not contain any controlled substances or levels of
6 residual solvents higher than is allowed in the United States Pharmacopeia 467.
7 (3) "Kratom processor" means a person who manufacturers or produces kratom products.
8 (4) "Kratom product" means a finished article containing any part of a leaf of the plant Mitragyna
9 speciosa in fresh, dehydrated, or dried form, or a kratom extract, including kratom beverages prepared and sold
10 in food establishments.
11 (5) "Synthesized material" means an alkaloid, metabolite, or alkaloid derivative that has been
12 created by chemical synthesis or biosynthetic means, including but not limited to fermentation, recombinant
13 techniques, or yeast-derived, enzymatic techniques, rather than traditional food preparation techniques, such
14 as heating or extracting, that synthetically alters the composition of any kratom alkaloid or constituent.
15
16 NEW SECTION. Section 3. Kratom product restrictions -- exemption for entities that provide
17 fresh kratom products to public. (1) A kratom processor may not prepare, distribute, sell, or expose for sale a
18 kratom product that:
19 (a) contains a level of 7-hydroxymitragynine in the alkaloid fraction that is greater than 2% of the
20 alkaloid composition of the kratom product;
21 (b) contains synthesized material;
22 (c) contains or is adulterated with a dangerous non-kratom substance if it contains a poisonous or
23 otherwise deleterious non-kratom ingredient, including but not limited to the substances listed as a controlled
24 substances under state or federal law; and
25 (d) is combustible, intended to be used for vaporization, or injectable.
26 (2) [Sections 1 through 3] also apply to entities that are open to the public in physical locations that
